## 📊 Dry Run Example

Input:

```
[30,38,30,36,35,40,28]
```

| Day | Temp | Stack                            | Result |
| --- | ---- | -------------------------------- | ------ |
| 0   | 30   | [0]                              |        |
| 1   | 38   | pop 0 → res[0]=1                 | [1]    |
| 2   | 30   | [1,2]                            |        |
| 3   | 36   | pop 2 → res[2]=1                 | [1,3]  |
| 4   | 35   | [1,3,4]                          |        |
| 5   | 40   | pop 4 →1<br>pop 3 →2<br>pop 1 →4 | [5]    |
| 6   | 28   | [5,6]                            |        |

Final:

```
[1,4,1,2,1,0,0]
```

---

## 🎯 Why It Works

Stack always keeps **indexes of temperatures that are waiting for a warmer day**.

When we find a warmer temperature:

* We resolve all smaller temperatures in stack.
* Remove them.
* Fill their result.

Remaining elements in stack at end → no warmer day → 0.

---

## ⏱ Time & Space Complexity

| Type  | Complexity |
| ----- | ---------- |
| Time  | O(n)       |
| Space | O(n)       |

Because:

* Each element pushed once
* Each element popped once

---

## 🧩 When To Use Monotonic Stack?

Use when question says:

* Next Greater Element
* Next Smaller Element
* Previous Greater
* Daily Temperatures
* Stock Span Problem
* Largest Rectangle in Histogram

